Project Overview¶

Data Overview¶

Input X:

  • A static station graph (connectivity between Indego stations)
  • A temporal sequence of node features for each station, including:
  • historical demand
  • weather
  • temporal context
  • station attributes (location, capacity, amenities accessibility)

Output y:

  • The next-hour demand for each station.

Table 1. Primary Data Sources | Category | Dataset Name | File(s) Used | Provider / Link | Description | | ----------------------- | ------------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | | Bike trips | Indego Trip Data | indego-trips-20232025 (multiple CSVs) | https://www.rideindego.com/about/data/ | Raw trip-level data (start/end time, station, direction, pass type, bike type). Used to aggregate to stationhour demand. | | Station information | Indego Stations Table | indego-stations-2025-10-01.csv | https://www.rideindego.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/indego-stations-2025-10-01.csv | Provides station metadata: ID, name, coordinates, activation status. Used for spatial joins and amenities computation. | | Station live feed | Indego All Stations (API) | (used for reference) | https://kiosks.bicycletransit.workers.dev/phl | Live GeoJSON of all stations (coords, dock capacity). Not directly used in modeling but validates station locations. | | Weather | PHL ASOS Hourly Weather | (retrieved via requests) | https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/cgi-bin/request/asos.py | Hourly weather observations from Philadelphia International Airport (PHL): temperature, precipitation, wind, humidity. Used as time-varying environmental predictors. | | Census | ACS demographic variables | (retrieved via pytidycensus) | https://pypi.org/project/pytidycensus/ | Census variables (e.g., population, income). Currently optionalmay be included in extended models or spatial context. |

Table 2. Amenities Data Sources | Amenity Category | Dataset Name | File Used | Provider / Link | Description | | ---------------------- | -------------------------------- | ------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | | Transit (Bus) | Bus Shelters | bus_transit_shelters.geojson | https://opendataphilly.org/datasets/bus-shelters/ | All bus shelters in Philadelphia. Used to compute number of bus stops within 500m/1000m of each station. | | Transit (Trolley) | SEPTA Trolley Stops | Trolley_Stations.geojson | https://opendataphilly.org/datasets/septa-routes-stops-locations/ | All trolley stops. Used for trolley access metrics. | | Transit (Rail) | SEPTA Regional Rail | Regional_Rail_Stations.geojson | https://opendataphilly.org/datasets/septa-routes-stops-locations/ | Regional rail stations. Used to quantify rail-based accessibility. | | Parks & Recreation | Parks & Recreation Program Sites | PPR_Program_Sites.geojson | https://opendataphilly.org/datasets/parks-recreation-program-sites/ | Points representing parks, rec centers, and program sites. Used for greenspace availability. | | Schools | Schools | Schools.geojson | https://opendataphilly.org/datasets/schools/ | Public/charter/private school locations. Used for educational environment indicators. | | Hospitals | Hospitals | Hospitals.geojson | https://opendataphilly.org/datasets/philadelphia-hospitals/ | All licensed hospitals in Philadelphia. Used for distance-to-healthcare and accessibility measurements. |

Table 3. Final Modeling Files (to be generated during preprocessing) | File Name | Description | Generated In | | ---------------------- | --------------------------------------------- | ----------------------- | | station_hourly.csv | Hourly demand per station + temporal features | Trips preprocessing | | weather_hourly.csv | Hourly weather aligned to Indego timeline | Weather preprocessing | | amenities_features.csv | One row per station with spatial features | Amenities preprocessing | | model_input_train.csv | Final training set (merged all features) | Feature engineering | | model_input_test.csv | Final test set | Feature engineering |

from datetime import datetime
import requests
from io import StringIO

def fetch_asos_data(station, start_date, end_date):
    """
    Fetch ASOS weather data from IEM using their web service API.
    Station: airport code ('PHL' for Philadelphia International)
    """
    base_url = "https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/cgi-bin/request/asos.py"
    
    params = {
        'station': station,
        'data': ['tmpf', 'dwpf', 'sknt', 'p01i', 'relh'],
        'year1': start_date.year,
        'month1': start_date.month,
        'day1': start_date.day,
        'year2': end_date.year,
        'month2': end_date.month,
        'day2': end_date.day,
        'tz': 'America/New_York',
        'format': 'onlycomma',
        'latlon': 'no',
        'elev': 'no',
        'missing': 'null',
        'trace': '0.0001',
        'direct': 'no',
    }
    
    response = requests.get(base_url, params=params)
    print("Request URL:", response.url[:200], "...")
    
    if response.status_code == 200:
        df = pd.read_csv(
            StringIO(response.text),
            na_values=['null', 'M']
        )
        return df
    else:
        raise Exception(f"Failed to fetch data: {response.status_code}\n{response.text}")

weather_hourly = (
    weather_valid
    .set_index('datetime')
    .resample('h')
    .agg({
        'temperature_F': 'mean',       
        'dew_point_F': 'mean',
        'wind_speed_knots': 'mean',
        'precip_in': 'sum',             
        'relative_humidity': 'mean'
    })
    .reset_index()
)

# 1. Gender ratio
acs_raw["pct_male"]   = acs_raw["pop_male"] / acs_raw["pop_total"]
acs_raw["pct_female"] = acs_raw["pop_female"] / acs_raw["pop_total"]
# 2. Age structure
acs_raw["pct_age20_34"] = (
    acs_raw["age_20_24"] +
    acs_raw["age_25_29"] +
    acs_raw["age_30_34"]
) / acs_raw["pop_total"]

acs_raw["pct_age35_44"] = acs_raw["age_35_44"] / acs_raw["pop_total"]
# 3. Race & ethnicity structure
acs_raw["pct_white"]    = acs_raw["white"] / acs_raw["pop_total"]
acs_raw["pct_black"]    = acs_raw["black"] / acs_raw["pop_total"]
acs_raw["pct_hispanic"] = acs_raw["hispanic"] / acs_raw["pop_total"]
# 4. Education attainment
acs_raw["pct_higher_edu"] = (
    acs_raw["bachelors"] +
    acs_raw["masters"] +
    acs_raw["doctorate"]
) / acs_raw["pop_total"]
# 5. Poverty rate
acs_raw["pct_poverty"] = acs_raw["pop_poverty"] / acs_raw["pop_total"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------
# STEP 1: Build station-hour level demand dataset
# ---------------------------------------------------------------


# ---------------------------------------------------------------
# Combine all trip datasets (train / val / test)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------

# Adjust these names if your variables differ
trips_all = pd.concat(
    [trips_2023, trips_2024, trips_2025],
    ignore_index=True
)

# Adjust column names according to your dataset
station_col = "start_station"      # e.g., "start_station_id"
time_col    = "start_time"         # datetime column

# Ensure time column is in datetime format
trips_all[time_col] = pd.to_datetime(trips_all[time_col], errors="coerce")
trips_all = trips_all.dropna(subset=[time_col])   # Remove invalid timestamp rows

# Floor timestamps to hourly resolution
trips_all["timestamp_hour"] = trips_all[time_col].dt.floor("h")

# ---------------------------------------------------------------
# Aggregate to station-hour demand
# ---------------------------------------------------------------

station_hour_counts = (
    trips_all
    .groupby([station_col, "timestamp_hour"])
    .size()
    .rename("demand")
)

# ---------------------------------------------------------------
# Reindex to ensure every station has every hour (fill missing hours with 0)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------

# Determine full time range
min_time = station_hour_counts.index.get_level_values("timestamp_hour").min()
max_time = station_hour_counts.index.get_level_values("timestamp_hour").max()

# Get list of all stations
stations = np.sort(trips_all[station_col].unique())

# Create complete hourly index for all stations
full_time_index = pd.date_range(min_time, max_time, freq="h")
full_index = pd.MultiIndex.from_product(
    [stations, full_time_index],
    names=[station_col, "timestamp_hour"]
)

# Reindex and fill missing demand with zeros
station_hourly = (
    station_hour_counts
    .reindex(full_index, fill_value=0)
    .reset_index()
)

# ---------------------------------------------------------------
# Add temporal features
# ---------------------------------------------------------------

station_hourly["hour"] = station_hourly["timestamp_hour"].dt.hour
station_hourly["weekday"] = station_hourly["timestamp_hour"].dt.weekday  # Monday=0
station_hourly["is_weekend"] = station_hourly["weekday"].isin([5, 6]).astype(int)
station_hourly["month"] = station_hourly["timestamp_hour"].dt.month

# Simple season mapping
def month_to_season(m):
    if m in [12, 1, 2]:
        return "winter"
    elif m in [3, 4, 5]:
        return "spring"
    elif m in [6, 7, 8]:
        return "summer"
    else:
        return "fall"

station_hourly["season"] = station_hourly["month"].apply(month_to_season)

# ---------------------------------------------------------------
# Historical demand features
# ---------------------------------------------------------------

# Sort to ensure correct temporal order
station_hourly = station_hourly.sort_values([station_col, "timestamp_hour"])

# Lag-1 demand (previous hour)
station_hourly["demand_lag1"] = (
    station_hourly
    .groupby(station_col)["demand"]
    .shift(1)
)

# 3-hour moving average based on the previous 3 hours
station_hourly["demand_ma3"] = (
    station_hourly
    .groupby(station_col)["demand"]
    .transform(lambda s: s.shift(1).rolling(window=3, min_periods=1).mean())
)

# ---------------------------------------------------------------
# Save intermediate dataset
# ---------------------------------------------------------------

output_dir = Path.cwd().parents[1] / "data/processed"
output_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

station_hourly_path = output_dir / "station_hourly_basic.csv"
station_hourly.to_csv(station_hourly_path, index=False)

hospitals_src= hospitals_clipped      if "hospitals_clipped"      in globals() else hospitals


def count_within_buffer(station_gdf, amenity_gdf, radius_m, id_col="start_station"):
    """
    For each station, count how many amenities fall within a buffer of radius_m.
    Returns a DataFrame indexed by station id with a 'count' column.
    """
    # Project to a metric CRS
    stations_m = station_gdf.to_crs(epsg=26918)
    amenity_m  = amenity_gdf.to_crs(epsg=26918)

    # Buffer around stations
    buffers = stations_m.copy()
    buffers["geometry"] = buffers.buffer(radius_m)

    # Spatial join: amenities within station buffers
    joined = gpd.sjoin(
        amenity_m,
        buffers[[id_col, "geometry"]],
        how="left",
        predicate="within"
    )

    counts = (
        joined.groupby(id_col)
        .size()
        .rename("count")
        .to_frame()
    )

    counts = counts.reindex(station_gdf[id_col]).fillna(0).astype(int)
    return counts


def nearest_distance(station_gdf, amenity_gdf, id_col="start_station"):
    """
    For each station, compute distance (meters) to the nearest amenity.
    """
    stations_m = station_gdf.to_crs(epsg=26918)
    amenity_m  = amenity_gdf.to_crs(epsg=26918)

    joined = gpd.sjoin_nearest(
        stations_m[[id_col, "geometry"]],
        amenity_m[["geometry"]],
        how="left",
        distance_col="dist_m"
    )

    dist = joined.set_index(id_col)[["dist_m"]]
    return dist

# Build K-NN Adjacency Matrix

def build_adjacency_matrix(stations_gdf, k=5):
    """
    Build k-nearest neighbor adjacency matrix from station coordinates.
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    stations_gdf : GeoDataFrame
        Contains station geometries (EPSG:4326)
    k : int
        Number of nearest neighbors
    
    Returns:
    --------
    A : (N, N) sparse adjacency matrix (row-normalized)
    """
    
    # Extract coordinates in UTM (meters)
    stations_utm = stations_gdf.to_crs('EPSG:26918').copy()
    coords = np.array([[geom.x, geom.y] for geom in stations_utm.geometry])
    
    N = len(coords)
    
    # Compute pairwise distances
    distances = cdist(coords, coords, metric='euclidean')
    
    # Find k+1 nearest neighbors (including self)
    neighbors = np.argsort(distances, axis=1)[:, :k+1]
    
    # Build adjacency matrix with inverse-distance weighting
    A = np.zeros((N, N))
    for i in range(N):
        for j in neighbors[i]:
            if i != j:
                dist = distances[i, j]
                if dist > 0:
                    A[i, j] = 1.0 / dist
    
    # Row normalization
    row_sum = A.sum(axis=1, keepdims=True)
    row_sum[row_sum == 0] = 1
    A = A / row_sum
    
    return torch.tensor(A, dtype=torch.float32)

# Build Sequence Dataset
from numpy.lib.stride_tricks import sliding_window_view

def build_sequences(X, y, T_in=24):
    N_samples, N_stations, N_features = X.shape
    
    # Sliding window
    X_seq = sliding_window_view(X, T_in, axis=0)  # (N-T_in, N_stations, N_features, T_in)
    X_seq = X_seq.transpose(0, 3, 1, 2)  # (N-T_in, T_in, N_stations, N_features)
    y_seq = y[T_in:]  # (N-T_in, N_stations)
    
    return torch.tensor(X_seq, dtype=torch.float32), torch.tensor(y_seq, dtype=torch.float32)
In [48]:
def build_sequences_numpy(X, y, T_in=24):
    N_samples, N_stations, N_features = X.shape
    
    # Sliding window
    X_seq = sliding_window_view(X, T_in, axis=0)  # (N-T_in, N_stations, N_features, T_in)
    X_seq = X_seq.transpose(0, 3, 1, 2)  # (N-T_in, T_in, N_stations, N_features)
    X_seq = X_seq[:-1]
    y_seq = y[T_in:]  # (N-T_in, N_stations)
    
    # numpy array
    return X_seq, y_seq

# Graph Convolutional Network Layer

class GCNLayer(nn.Module):
    """
    Single-layer Graph Convolutional Network (GCN).
    Aggregates features from neighboring stations using the adjacency matrix.
    """
    def __init__(self, input_dim, output_dim, dropout=0.0):
        super(GCNLayer, self).__init__()
        self.linear = nn.Linear(input_dim, output_dim)
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(dropout)
    
    def forward(self, X, A):
        """
        X: (B, N, input_dim) - batch of node features
        A: (N, N) - adjacency matrix
        Returns: (B, N, output_dim)
        """
        # Linear transformation
        X_transformed = self.linear(X)  # (B, N, output_dim)
        
        # Apply adjacency matrix (spatial aggregation)
        out = torch.matmul(A, X_transformed)  # (B, N, output_dim)
        
        # Apply activation
        out = self.relu(out)
        out = self.dropout(out)  # Dropout

        return out

# ST-GNN+RNN Model

class GNNGRU(nn.Module):
    """
    Spatio-Temporal Graph Neural Network + Recurrent Neural Network.
    
    Architecture:
    1. For each time step, apply GCN to capture spatial relationships
    2. Feed spatial features into GRU to capture temporal dependencies
    3. Output prediction for next hour
    """
    def __init__(self, input_dim, gcn_hidden, gru_hidden, dropout=0.0):
        super(GNNGRU, self).__init__()
        self.gcn = GCNLayer(input_dim, gcn_hidden, dropout=dropout)
        self.gru = nn.GRU(gcn_hidden, gru_hidden, batch_first=True)
        self.fc = nn.Linear(gru_hidden, 1)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(dropout)
    
    def forward(self, X, A):
        """
        Forward pass through ST-GNN+RNN.
        
        Parameters:
        -----------
        X : (B, T_in, N, F) tensor
            Batch of sequences: (batch_size, time_steps, num_stations, features)
        A : (N, N) tensor
            Station adjacency matrix
        
        Returns:
        --------
        y_pred : (B, N) tensor
            Predicted next-hour demand for each station
        """
        B, T_in, N, F = X.shape
        
        # Apply GCN to each time step
        X_gcn_list = []
        for t in range(T_in):
            X_t = X[:, t, :, :]  # (B, N, F)
            X_gcn_t = self.gcn(X_t, A)  # (B, N, gcn_hidden)
            X_gcn_list.append(X_gcn_t)
        
        # Stack temporal dimension
        X_gcn = torch.stack(X_gcn_list, dim=1)  # (B, T_in, N, gcn_hidden)
        
        # Reshape for GRU: treat each station independently
        B, T, N, H_gcn = X_gcn.shape
        X_gcn_flat = X_gcn.permute(0, 2, 1, 3).reshape(B * N, T, H_gcn)  # (B*N, T_in, gcn_hidden)
        
        # Apply GRU
        _, h_n = self.gru(X_gcn_flat)  # h_n: (1, B*N, gru_hidden)
        h_n = h_n.squeeze(0)  # (B*N, gru_hidden)
        
        h_n = self.dropout(h_n)


        # Predict demand for next hour
        y_pred_flat = self.fc(h_n)  # (B*N, 1)
        
        # Reshape back to (B, N)
        y_pred = y_pred_flat.reshape(B, N)
        
        return y_pred

from torch.utils.data import Dataset, DataLoader

class BikeDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, X, y):
        self.X = X  # numpy array
        self.y = y  # numpy array
    
    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.X)
    
    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        
        return torch.tensor(self.X[idx], dtype=torch.float32), \
               torch.tensor(self.y[idx], dtype=torch.float32)

# Training loop
print("Training GNN+RNN model...")
for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    # Training
    model.train()
    train_loss = 0
    for i in range(0, len(X_train_seq), batch_size):
        batch_end = min(i + batch_size, len(X_train_seq))
        X_batch = torch.tensor(X_train_seq[i:batch_end], dtype=torch.float32).to(device)
        y_batch = torch.tensor(y_train_seq[i:batch_end], dtype=torch.float32).to(device)
        
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        y_pred = model(X_batch, A)
        loss = criterion(y_pred, y_batch)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        
        train_loss += loss.item()
    torch.cuda.empty_cache()

    # Validation
    model.eval()
    val_preds = []
    with torch.no_grad():
        for X_val_batch, _ in val_loader: 
            X_val_batch = X_val_batch.to(device)
            y_val_batch_pred = model(X_val_batch, A).cpu().numpy()
            val_preds.append(y_val_batch_pred)
    
    y_val_pred = np.concatenate(val_preds, axis=0)
    val_loss = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_val_seq, y_val_pred))

    # Learning rate scheduling
    scheduler.step(val_loss)
    current_lr = optimizer.param_groups[0]['lr']

    # Early stopping
    if val_loss < best_val_rmse:
        best_val_rmse = val_loss
        patience_counter = 0
        best_model_state = model.state_dict().copy()
        print(f"Epoch {epoch+1}/{num_epochs} | Train Loss: {train_loss/max(1, len(X_train_seq)//batch_size):.4f} | Val RMSE: {val_loss:.4f}  NEW BEST")
    else:
        patience_counter += 1
        print(f"Epoch {epoch+1}/{num_epochs} | Train Loss: {train_loss/max(1, len(X_train_seq)//batch_size):.4f} | Val RMSE: {val_loss:.4f}")
        if patience_counter >= patience:
            print(f"\nEarly stopping at epoch {epoch+1}")
            model.load_state_dict(best_model_state)
            break

print(f"\n Training complete! Best Val RMSE: {best_val_rmse:.4f}")

# GNN+RNN (using pre-calculated variables)
gnn_val_mae = val_mae_gnn
gnn_val_rmse = val_rmse_gnn
gnn_test_mae = test_mae
gnn_test_rmse = test_rmse

# ===== Create comparison dataframe =====
results = {
    'Model': ['Linear Regression', 'GNN+RNN'],
    'Val MAE': [lr_val_mae, gnn_val_mae],
    'Val RMSE': [lr_val_rmse, gnn_val_rmse],
    'Test MAE': [lr_test_mae, gnn_test_mae],
    'Test RMSE': [lr_test_rmse, gnn_test_rmse]
}

results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)

# ===== Print results table =====
print("\n" + results_df.to_string(index=False))
print("\n" + "="*60)

# ===== Print comparison =====
print("\nMETRIC COMPARISON:")
print(f"\nValidation RMSE:")
print(f"  Linear Regression: {lr_val_rmse:.4f}")
print(f"  GNN+RNN:          {gnn_val_rmse:.4f}")
if gnn_val_rmse < lr_val_rmse:
    print(f"   GNN+RNN is better by {((lr_val_rmse - gnn_val_rmse) / lr_val_rmse * 100):.2f}%")
else:
    print(f"   Linear Regression is better by {((gnn_val_rmse - lr_val_rmse) / lr_val_rmse * 100):.2f}%")

print(f"\nTest RMSE:")
print(f"  Linear Regression: {lr_test_rmse:.4f}")
print(f"  GNN+RNN:          {gnn_test_rmse:.4f}")
if gnn_test_rmse < lr_test_rmse:
    print(f"   GNN+RNN is better by {((lr_test_rmse - gnn_test_rmse) / lr_test_rmse * 100):.2f}%")
else:
    print(f"   Linear Regression is better by {((gnn_test_rmse - lr_test_rmse) / lr_test_rmse * 100):.2f}%")

print(f"\nTest MAE:")
print(f"  Linear Regression: {lr_test_mae:.4f}")
print(f"  GNN+RNN:          {gnn_test_mae:.4f}")
if gnn_test_mae < lr_test_mae:
    print(f"   GNN+RNN is better by {((lr_test_mae - gnn_test_mae) / lr_test_mae * 100):.2f}%")
else:
    print(f"   Linear Regression is better by {((gnn_test_mae - lr_test_mae) / lr_test_mae * 100):.2f}%")

# ===== Summary =====
print("\n" + "="*60)
print("SUMMARY:")
print("="*60)

baseline_test_rmse = lr_test_rmse
baseline_test_mae = lr_test_mae

rmse_improvement = (baseline_test_rmse - gnn_test_rmse) / baseline_test_rmse * 100
mae_improvement = (baseline_test_mae - gnn_test_mae) / baseline_test_mae * 100

print(f"\nGNN+RNN performance relative to Linear Regression baseline:")
print(f"  Test RMSE: {rmse_improvement:+.2f}%")
print(f"  Test MAE:  {mae_improvement:+.2f}%")

if rmse_improvement > 0 and mae_improvement > 0:
    print(f"\n GNN+RNN outperforms Linear Regression on both metrics!")
elif rmse_improvement > 0 or mae_improvement > 0:
    print(f"\n GNN+RNN shows mixed results compared to Linear Regression")
else:
    print(f"\n Linear Regression currently outperforms GNN+RNN")
    print(f"  Consider: increasing model capacity, adjusting hyperparameters, or training longer")
